# Using Google Colab for wriing and running my code.
# So wanted to zip the spotipy package so that it can be used to add layers in AWS Lambda function.
import shutil
import os
import sys

# Get the path where spotipy is installed
spotipy_path = None
print(sys.path)
for path in sys.path:
    if '/usr/local/lib/python3.10/dist-packages' in path:
        spotipy_path = os.path.join(path, 'spotipy')
        break

if spotipy_path:
    # Path for the zip file
    zip_file_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/spotipy.zip'

    # Create a zip file
    shutil.make_archive(zip_file_path.split('.')[0], 'zip', spotipy_path)

    # Check if the zip file has been created
    if os.path.exists(zip_file_path):
        print(f"spotipy folder zipped successfully. You can download it from: {zip_file_path}")
    else:
        print("Failed to create the zip file.")
else:
    print("spotipy package not found.")

The above way of creating df_album is easy to interpret but in not efficient for very large datasets as it needs intermediate list creation resulting in more memory usage. The better option is using dictionary and then creating dataframes from them. Below is the code.

In [24]:
album_list=[]
for item in data['items']:
  ID=item['track']['album']['id']
  Album_Name= item['track']['album']['name']
  Release_Date=item['track']['album']['release_date']
  Total_Tracks=item['track']['album']['total_tracks']
  External_URL=item['track']['album']['external_urls']['spotify']
  album_list.append({'ID':ID,'Album_Name':Album_Name,'Release_Date':Release_Date,'Total_Tracks':Total_Tracks, 'External_URL':External_URL})

artist_list=[]
for item in data['items']:
  artist=item['track']['album']['artists']
  for each_artist in artist:
    artist_id=each_artist['id']
    artist_name=each_artist['name']
    external_url=each_artist['href']

songs_list=[]
for item in data['items']:
  song_id=item['track']['id']
  song_name=item['track']['name']
  song_duration_ms=item['track']['duration_ms']
  song_url=item['track']['external_urls']['spotify']
  song_popularity=item['track']['popularity']
  song_added=item['added_at']
  album_id=item['track']['album']['id']
  artist_id=item['track']['album']['artists'][0]['id']
  songs_list.append({'Song_ID':song_id,'Name':song_name,'Duration_ms':song_duration_ms,'URL':song_url,'Popularity':song_popularity,'Added_At':song_added,'Album_ID':album_id,'Artist_ID':artist_id})

album_df['Release_Date']=pd.to_datetime(album_df['Release_Date']) how can this be fixed getting warning

<ipython-input-54-5a2ea00c2fe7>:1: SettingWithCopyWarning: A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame. Try using .loc[row_indexer,col_indexer] = value instead

See the caveats in the documentation: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/indexing.html#returning-a-view-versus-a-copy album_df['Release_Date']=pd.to_datetime(album_df['Release_Date']).copy()

Solution: The warning you're encountering suggests that you're trying to modify a slice of the DataFrame directly, which can lead to unexpected behavior. You can fix this by using .loc[row_indexer, col_indexer] to explicitly assign the values. Here's how you can do it:

album_df.loc[:, 'Release_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(album_df['Release_Date'])

This explicitly tells pandas to modify the original DataFrame rather than a slice of it, avoiding the warning.
